Crazy story, a girl I was crushing on for 20 years (since childhood) reached out to me end of 2020. She told me she was leaving her narcissistic husband of  about 20 years. He moved out with his mistress. 4 months in, I'm dreaming about this song and wake up about 3 am and she's silently crying next to me. I act like I don't see it try to go back to sleep.   I know what's going on. It's like the energy of him pulling her back was so strong impacted my dreams. She eventually left me 6 months in to go back. Just weeks later she's begging me not to give up on her and give her time to sort through her situation and come back to me.  I told in the break up process I had the dream of this song and new the day was coming. Oddly enough, she kept coming after me behind his back (which I allowed for a brief moment out of a vengeful mindset) and she has the nerve to send me this song when she finds out I'm talking to another girl. The past can be haunting, but as the saying goes, fool me once shame on you, fool me twice shame on me. If you didn't learn it didn't work the first time around for some substantive reasons, will it take another time of walking through the fire at your own expense to prove the point. Be smart, if it proved unworkable the first time around, people and circumstances don't change much, and importantly you can't change them. Oh chords from the past, how sweet they may sound against the shadows of the stark realities of the present. But old difficulties, differences and dilemmas were not spun from cobwebs that will magically be swept away by the present. They may just look appealing at the time due to the rose colored glasses we often tend to don when re-examining our past. If problems were unsolvable in the past, chances are, they will remain the same, if not more so in the future. Sometimes the past is best carried in your heart, remembering the good times, but leaving best enough alone. Godspeed.

I'm reading a book and doing a workbook called "The journey from Abandonment to Healing" by Susan Anderson.  She talked about the phenomenon of separating from someone you love deeply and then seeing them when they're not there.    She talks about the part of your brain that is triggered when separated from someone you loved is equivalent to a mother losing her child,  the brain kicks into overdrive to help you to be able to recognize the person in a crowd,  and send signals to your body that this person is needed for your survival.    I'm not explaining it perfectly i know ğŸ¤£ğŸ¤£ğŸ¤£ but this video made me think of it!   When i separated from an ex this would happen to me alll the time and I would feel so crazy!! Thinking I saw, felt, or heard his voice when he wasn't there!

You can see the gravity of their choice in their faces in the final few seconds of the video. It actually looks to be a reference to The Graduate. The movie that started the trope of women running out of weddings in romantic comedies. It's funny because all the movies that copy it make this seem like a happy ending, but the original shows just how awkward it would be. I'm glad this video referenced that. Whether they stay together or not, they will have to work on their relationship just like everyone else, and it won't be easy.  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ahFARm2j38c

Just the right amount of toxicity I needed to hear
Let me clarify for people. Tiktok does not technically ruin songs or just make them popular. There are two categories to this phenomenon.   Category 1, nostalgia: this happens when person one has been listening to a song or artist for years and usually has nostalgic memories attached to it. When this person sees the song or artist get more recognition the rare nostalgic memory begins to fade and being replaced with memories of Charlie demelo dancing. This will cause person one to get mad at tiktok and new listeners. Person one can often be found saying, "I remember when this song came out" "this song is so nostalgic" "who knows this song not from tiktok". Person one can sometimes be called a "gate keeper". Songs in this category include: hopelessly devoted, future brake up song, put your head on my shoulder and more  Category 2, pop song: a song gets popular and person two is enjoying the song. They scroll through tiktok but while they are scrolling they keep hearing the same song over and over again so the get sick of it and move on. This is why songs that stayed at the top of charts like "old town road" and "despasito" are going extinct because tiktok has us going through songs way to fast. Songs in this category include: savage, WAP, excitment, say so and many more.  Notice how tiktok dosen't just "make songs popular" (new listeners from cadigory 1 or late listeners from cadigory 2) it milks the hell out of songs till they get old  Notice how tiktok never "ruins songs" (gate keepers from cadigory 1 and early listeners from cadigory 2) it just messes up the nostalgia factor for person one

Read the whole uncensored Bible that is Catholic(The Original) andÂ  pray my friends. Wish you all wellğŸ™amenğŸ™   Was the Jesus of the Bible who He claimed He was? Was He really God's Son? Was Jesus the Messiah? There are over 300 propheciesÂ  that point directly to the Messiah. Here is an example of just 8 : The time of His birth (see the Daniel 8 & 9 Timeline). He would be born in Bethlehem. (Micah 5:2) He would be born of a virgin. (Isaiah 7:14) He would be betrayed for 30 pieces of silver. (Zechariah 11:12) He would be mocked. (Psalm 22:7,8) He would be crucified. (John 3:14) He would be pierced. (Psalms 22:16) He would die with the wicked, but He would be buried with the rich. (Isaiah 53:9)   Mathematics & Astronomy Professor Peter W. Stoner has made the statement that the chances of just 8 prophecies (like these) coming true by sheer chance is 1 in 10Â¹â·(100,000,000,000,000,000). That would be equivalent to covering the whole state of Texas with silver dollars two feet deep and then expecting a blindfolded man to walk across the state and on the very first try find the ONE coin you marked (roughly equivalent to the Province of Ontario being 1.5 feet deep).  And if we were to add only 8 more similar prophecies, for a total of 16, the odds would be 1 x 10Â²â¸ x 10Â¹â· or 1 in 10â´âµ (1,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000)  Using the same type of illustration as above, if we were to press this many silver dollars(10â´âµ) into a ball and place the center of this ball where the center of our Sun is, this silver ball's outer edge would be in approximately the same area as the orbit of Neptune (almost to Pluto.). One man fulfilling all 16 prophecies by sheer chance would be like sending a blind-folded person out to find one specific silver dollar that has been marked and has been mixed up somewhere in this huge ball and actually finding it the first time! (Keep in mind that this is a three-dimensional BALL, not a disk like our Solar System.)   Professor Stoner gives us yet another illustration, but this time, because a silver dollar, and even the atom, would be too large for this one he chose to use just the electron that orbits the nucleus of the atom.Â  The electron is one of the smallest particles of matter known to man. It is so small that if you lined up 2.5 x 10Â¹âµ (2,500,000,000,000,000) single file you would end up with a line that is only 1 inch long. (If we were going to count the electrons in this line one inch long, and counted 250 each minute, and if we counted day and night, it would take us 19,000,000 years to count just the one-inch line of electrons.) Now back to Stoner's illustration. Using only 48 of the prophecies that Jesus fulfilled it was calculated that the chances of one person fulfilling these by sheer chance would be 1 in 10Â¹âµâ·To help us understand how huge this number is he suggested taking 10Â¹âµâ· electrons and pressing them into a solid ball. This ball, made entirely of electrons, would pretty much fill, not just our galaxy, but the entire known universe. (At the time Stoner's book was written the universe was known to be at least 6 billion light years in all directions. Stoner's known universe would need to be filled about 10,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 times.) Once again we would mark just one electron, blindfold a man and send him out to find that one electron. Peter Stoner then states, "To the extent, then, that we know this blindfolded man cannot pick out the marked electron, we know that the Bible is inspired. This is not merely evidence. It is proof of the Bible's inspiration by God--proof so definite that the universe is not large enough to hold the evidence." Professor Stoner then made the comment that, "Any man who rejects Christ as the Son of God is rejecting a fact proved perhaps more absolutely than any other fact in the world."
